Since in bending rigid bodies the convex side comes thus to be lengthened and the concave to be shortened, the result is that the thinner rigid bodies are, the more and the more easily can they be bent, for although glass is very fragile and can scarcely be beot, yet fine threads ¹ of it can be wound round a bobbin and tied in a knot.
